      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm running a linear regression on some housing price data but my residual plots are looking pretty messy. The residuals don't look normally distributed at all, and I'm seeing some pretty heavy skewness. What's the best way to handle this to fix the violation of the normality assumption?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Messy residual plots, especially with heavy skewness, can be a real headache for your linear regression, but don't let it scare you. You can try a few things, though sometimes the best fix is just to acknowledge that the model isn't quite fitting the data as perfectly as you'd like. You might consider transforming your dependent variable or the residuals themselves to try and pull that distribution closer to a normal shape.\n\nFor instance, a log transformation on the housing prices might help if the skewness is due to the price data being heavily skewed. If the residuals themselves are the problem, you could try a Box-Cox transformation on the residuals. Remember, a good transformation is often just a matter of trial and error, and you'll need to check your plots again after each step.",
      "source": "target",
