    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Thanks, I'll try the log transform. I'm also seeing a few extreme outliers on the high end that seem to be pulling the whole distribution away from the mean. Do those specific outliers fundamentally break the regression, or can I just leave them in and hope the transformation fixes the normality issue?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Outliers, especially those high-end ones, are a real concern, and they can certainly pull the regression line in a direction that makes your assumptions look shaky. They don't necessarily *fundamentally* break the regression, but they can definitely inflate your standard errors and make your model less reliable. It's a good idea to investigate those specific outliers, see if they are data entry errors, or if they represent genuine, albeit extreme, housing market realities.\n\nIf you leave them in, the log transformation might help the *distribution* of the residuals, but those extreme points will still exert a strong pull on the regression coefficients. It's often better to address the outliers first, perhaps by winsorizing them (capping them at a certain percentile) or by using a robust regression method that is less sensitive to those extreme values.",
      "source": "target",
